Agriculture and Biotechnology, China Agricultural Univ., And Key Laboratory of Farming System, Ministry of Agriculture, No. 2 Yuanmingyuan Xi Rd., Haidian District, Beijing 100193, China","The distribution and trends in reference evapotranspiration (ETo) are extremely important to water resources planning for agriculture, and it is widely believed that rates of ETo will increase with global warming. This is a big concern in China, where water deficits are common in the North China Plain (NCP). In this study, Penman-Monteith reference evapotranspiration at 26 meteorological stations during 1961-2006 in and around the NCP was calculated. The temporal variations and spatial distribution of ETo were analyzed and the causes for the variations were discussed. The results showed that: (1) the NCP was divided into two climatic regions based on aridity values: a semiarid region that accounts for 69% of the area and subhumid regions that made of the remaining area; (2) over the entire NCP, the highest annual ETo occurred in the central and western areas and the lowest total ETo was observed in the east. Comparing the mean monthly ETo and annual ETo distributions, the high ETo values from May through July mainly determined the annual ETo distribution; (3) for the whole NCP, annual ETo showed a statistically significant decrease of 11.92 mm/decade over the 46 years of data collection in the NCP or approximately a 5% total decrease compared to the ETo values in 1961; (4) to determine which variable has the greatest effect on the decrease in ETo, decadal changes were observed for daily values of maximum air temperature (+0.16°C), minimum air temperature (+0.35°C), net radiation (-0.13 MJ m-2), and mean wind speed (-0.09 m s-1). These results indicate that the decreasing net radiation and wind speed had a bigger impact on ETo rates than the increases observed by the maximum and minimum temperatures. © 2010 ASCE.","Climate change; Climate trends; Interpolation; Inverse distance weight; Spatial distribution","Air temperature; Climate trends; Climatic regions; Data collection; Decadal change; Inverse distance weight; Mean wind speed; Meteorological station; Net radiation; North China Plain; Penman-Monteith; Reference evapotranspiration; Semi-arid region; Spatial distribution; Subhumid regions; Temporal variation; Water deficits; Water resources planning; Western area; Wind speed; Arid regions; Atmospheric temperature; Evapotranspiration; Global warming; Interpolation; Plants (botany); Water supply; Wind effects; Size distribution; air temperature; climate change; evapotranspiration; global warming; interpolation; spatial distribution; water planning; water resource; wind velocity; China; North China Plain",,,,,,"Allen, R.G., Pereira, L.S., Raes, D., Smith, M., Crop evapotranspiration: Guidelines for computing crop water requirements (1998) Irri. and drain. paper no. 56, , FAO, Rome; Allen, R.G., (2005) The ASCE standardized reference evapotranspiration equation, , ASCE, Reston, Va; Bai, W., Feng, S., Kang, S., Reference crop evapotranspiration in Shanxi Province based on GIS (2006) Transactions of the CSAE, 22 (10), pp. 57-61. , in Chinese; Berengena, J., Gavilán, P., Márquez, F., Precisión de las estimaciones de la ETo en un ambiente advectivo (2001) Proc., 19th Congreso Nacional de Riegos, , Confederación Hidrográfica del Ebro, Zaragoza, España; Blaney, H.F., Criddle, W.D., Determining water requirements in irrigated areas from climatological and irrigation data (1950) Soil conservation service technical paper 96, , USDA, Washington, D.C; Brutsaert, W., Parlange, M.B., Hydrologic cycle explains the evaporation paradox (1998) Nature (London), 396, p. 30. , NATUAS, 0028-0836, 10.1038/23845; Cheng, J., Shi, Z., Zhu, Y., Assessment and mapping of environmental quality in agricultural soils of Zhejiang Province (2007) J. Environ. Sci., 19 (1), pp. 50-54. , 10.1016/S1001-0742(07)60008-4; Evapotranspiration and water irrigation requirements (1990) M